Kung Pao Chicken (for 2)
  --Cook's Illustrated

Chicken and Sauce:
12 oz boneless, skinless chicken thighs, trimmed and cut into 1/2" cubes
2 tbsp shoyu
1 1/2 tsp cornstarch
1 1/2 tsp chinese rice wine or dry sherry
1/4 tsp white pepper
1 1/2 tsp chinese black vinegar
1 1/2 tsp packed dark brown sugar
1 tsp toasted sesame oil

Combine chicken, 1 tbsp shoyu, cornstarch, wine, and white pepper in medium bowl and set aside. Stir vinegar, sugar, oil, and remaining 1 tbsp shoyu together in small bowl.

Stir Fry:
1 tsp minced garlic
1 tsp grated fresh ginger
3 1/2 tbsp vegetable oil, divided
1/4 c dry roasted peanuts
5-7 dried arbol chiles, halved lenghtwise and seeded
1/2 tsp sichuan peppercorns, ground coarse
1 celery rib, cut into 1/2" pieces
3 scallions, white and light green parts only, cut into 1/2" pieces

Stir garlic, ginger, and 1 1/2 tsp oil together in second small bowl. Combine peanuts and 1/2 tsp oil in 10" skillet over medium low heat. Cook, stirring constantly, until peanuts just being to darken, 3-5 min. Transfer peanuts to plate and spread into even layer to cool. Return empty skillet to medium low heat. Add remainig 1 1/2 tsp oil, arbols, and peppercorns and cook, stirring constantly, until arbols just begin to darken, 1-2 min. Add garlic mixture and cook, stirring constantly, until all clumps are broken up and mixture is fragrant, ~30 s. Add chicken and spread into even layer. Cover skillet, increase heat to medium high, and cook, without stirring, for 1 min. Add celery and cook uncovered, stirring frequently, until chicken is cooked through, 2-3 min. Add shoyu mixture and cook, stirring constantly, until sauce is thickened and shiny and coats chicken, ~2 min. Stir in scallions and peanuts. Transfer to platter and serve.


Notes: Use more/less chiles for your taste in heat level. If you can't find black vinegar, can sub sherry vinegar. 
